{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_9","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"cd /home/daytona/workspace/.fabro/scratch/01KRK15YVT2214YB2CZ78HWJJM/parallel/implementation_review_fanout/implementation_boilerplate_review && sed -n '1,240p' .workflow/iphone-app-factory/architecture.md\"","aggregated_output":"# WakeTask Architecture (SwiftAIBoilerplatePro-Mapped)\n\n## Purpose\nThis architecture implements WakeTask by extending `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro` and preserving boilerplate infrastructure boundaries required by the spec, DoD, and quality bar.\n\n## Product-to-Boilerplate Mapping\n\n| Boilerplate Module | WakeTask Use | Action |\n|---|---|---|\n| `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro.xcodeproj` | Primary app target, test targets, package wiring, CI entrypoint | Keep; extend target dependencies and schemes only as needed |\n| `Config/App.xcconfig` | App identity, build settings, flags for wake contract/escalation, test toggles | Keep; add WakeTask-specific keys via additive config |\n| `Packages/Core` | Domain models and use-cases: alarms, mission stack, wake contract, reliability ledger, first-task bridge | Extend heavily (new entities/services/use-cases) |\n| `Packages/Networking` | Remote config and optional telemetry transport outside critical wake path | Keep; minimal extension, no critical-flow hard dependency |\n| `Packages/Storage` | Local persistence for alarms, runs, mission outcomes, escalation timeline | Extend with WakeTask repositories and migrations |\n| `Packages/Auth` | Optional account identity/sync readiness, not required for MVP wake flow | Keep; no rebuild, mostly unchanged for MVP |\n| `Packages/Payments` | Subscription/paywall handling outside active wake path | Keep; strict separation from critical wake path |\n| `Packages/AI` | Adaptive mission rotation heuristics and anti-repeat policy support | Extend using existing AI abstractions |\n| `Packages/FeatureSettings` | Strictness, wake-check window, escalation profile, ad-free critical-path toggles | Extend with WakeTask settings surfaces |\n| `Packages/Localization` | User-facing wake flow copy, trust/privacy copy, ledger language | Extend string tables and localized resources |\n| `Packages/DesignSystem` | High-legibility controls, contrast-safe theming, large touch targets | Extend components/tokens; preserve DS conventions |\n| `CompositionRoot` | Dependency assembly: repositories, mission engine, wake-check scheduler, app shell routes | Extend factory wiring and environment injection |\n\n## Layering and Dependency Order\n1. `Config/App.xcconfig` and target settings establish compile-time flags.\n2. `Packages/Core` defines domain protocols/entities and use-cases.\n3. `Packages/Storage` and `Packages/Networking` implement infra adapters consumed by Core-facing repositories.\n4. `Packages/AI` provides mission-selection policy services consumed by Core.\n5. `Packages/Auth` and `Packages/Payments` stay optional integrations and must not block alarm execution.\n6. `Packages/FeatureSettings` and `Packages/Localization` provide runtime configuration and language resources for UI flows.\n7. `Packages/DesignSystem` renders all WakeTask UI surfaces with accessibility constraints.\n8. `CompositionRoot` composes implementations and injects view model dependencies into app flows in `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro`.\n\n## WakeTask Feature Architecture\n- Alarm Domain (`Core` + `Storage`): create/edit/enable alarms, strictness, mission stack persistence.\n- Mission Engine (`Core` + `AI`): select rotating modalities (cognitive/movement/scan-photo), anti-repeat safeguards.\n- Wake Contract (`Core` + scheduler infra): dismissal requires wake-check deadline; misses trigger escalation state.\n- Reliability Ledger (`Core` + `Storage`): append-only alarm-run timeline with success/failure reasons.\n- First-Task Bridge (`Core` + app shell UI): completion gate until first micro-task done.\n- Settings and Policy (`FeatureSettings`): user-configurable wake-check windows/escalation.\n\n## UI and Composition\n- App shell routes are extended to include onboarding, alarm setup, active alarm, wake-check, reliability ledger, and weekly consistency summary.\n- UI state lives in feature-specific view models; business rules stay in `Core` use-cases.\n- `DesignSystem` governs typography, spacing, color contrast, and min 44x44 pt interactions for all MVP flows.\n\n## Concurrency and Reliability\n- Swift 6 strict concurrency remains enabled.\n- Long-running wake timers/escalation scheduling use actor-safe state coordination and structured task cancellation.\n- Critical wake path avoids network hard dependencies; local storage is source of truth for wake execution.\n\n## Testing and Quality Gates\n- Unit tests: mission rotation logic, anti-repeat policy, wake-check deadline transitions.\n- Integration tests: persistence schema/order for reliability ledger entries.\n- UI tests: alarm setup/edit and first-task completion gate.\n- Performance tests: launch p95 <= 2.0s, mission interaction p95 <= 200ms.\n- Accessibility checks: Dynamic Type, VoiceOver labels, contrast AA, 44x44 targets.\n- CI gates: `xcodebuild build`, `xcodebuild test`, SwiftLint, SwiftFormat, Qlty, secret scan.\n- Exploratory QA: required Appium/XCUITest report at `reports/ios/appium-exploratory-report.json`.\n- Appium evidence source: hosted GitHub Actions macOS iOS simulator. allow_macos_deferred=false; local simulator limits and human testing are not acceptance evidence.\n\n## Non-Goals and Guardrails\n- No rebuild of auth/payments/AI/storage/networking/localization/settings/design system/DI.\n- No monetization interruptions in active alarm, dismiss, or wake-check flow.\n- No feature additions that violate MVP non-goals (sleep-stage platform, social feed, wearable dependency).\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_10","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"cd /home/daytona/workspace/.fabro/scratch/01KRK15YVT2214YB2CZ78HWJJM/parallel/implementation_review_fanout/implementation_boilerplate_review && sed -n '1,240p' .workflow/iphone-app-factory/adr.md\"","aggregated_output":"# ADR-001: WakeTask on SwiftAIBoilerplatePro\n\n## Status\nAccepted\n\n## Date\n2026-05-14\n\n## Context\nWakeTask must ship as a differentiated, reliability-first alarm experience while meeting:\n- Spec requirements (`FR-01..FR-06`, `NFR-01..NFR-06`)\n- Definition of Done gates (`DoD-01..DoD-18`)\n- Quality bar constraints, including mandatory boilerplate reuse and App Store 4.3 hardening.\n\nThe quality bar explicitly forbids rebuilding platform modules (auth, payments, AI, storage, networking, localization, settings, design system, DI/composition root) without explicit ADR justification.\n\n## Decision\nAdopt an extension-first architecture on `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro` with no module removals.\n\n### Module decisions\n- Keep and extend: `Packages/Core`, `Packages/Storage`, `Packages/AI`, `Packages/FeatureSettings`, `Packages/Localization`, `Packages/DesignSystem`, `CompositionRoot`, `Config/App.xcconfig`.\n- Keep with minimal/no MVP change: `Packages/Networking`, `Packages/Auth`, `Packages/Payments`, `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro.xcodeproj`.\n- Removed modules: none.\n\n## Dependency Order\n1. `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro.xcodeproj` + `Config/App.xcconfig` set build/runtime configuration.\n2. `Packages/Core` defines WakeTask domain and use-case contracts.\n3. `Packages/Storage` / `Packages/Networking` provide adapter implementations for repositories and external I/O.\n4. `Packages/AI` provides mission adaptation policies consumed by Core use-cases.\n5. `Packages/Auth` / `Packages/Payments` remain optional capability modules, not wake-path prerequisites.\n6. `Packages/FeatureSettings` and `Packages/Localization` supply runtime policy and copy for feature surfaces.\n7. `Packages/DesignSystem` supplies accessible UI primitives.\n8. `CompositionRoot` assembles dependency graph and routes app flows.\n\n## Rationale\n- Meets “extend before replace” contract and avoids schedule risk from platform rewrites.\n- Preserves tested package boundaries and CI setup already aligned to iOS quality gates.\n- Keeps critical wake path local-first and reliable while allowing optional integrations.\n- Supports App Store 4.3 differentiation by concentrating effort in product-specific behavior (ledger, wake contract, adaptive mission rotation, first-task bridge) rather than commodity infrastructure rebuild.\n\n## App Store 4.3 Consequences\n- Positive with this decision: differentiation is explicit in user-visible behavior (`D-01..D-04`) and not diluted by template-level reimplementation work.\n- If modules were removed/rebuilt without necessity:\n  - delivery risk increases, reducing confidence in polishing unique UX proof points;\n  - product can appear as a generic alarm clone with infrastructure churn but weak user-facing differentiation;\n  - review narrative weakens because custom work is not clearly tied to unique WakeTask outcomes.\n\nBecause no modules are removed, there is no dependency breakage introduced by this ADR.\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n- Full custom app architecture replacing boilerplate modules.\n  - Rejected: violates quality-bar default, increases risk/cost, weakens overnight delivery confidence.\n- Hybrid partial rebuild of selected infra modules.\n  - Rejected: insufficient value for MVP compared with extending current modules.\n\n## Verification Impact\nThis ADR requires:\n- architecture mapping in `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/architecture.md`.\n- CI evidence for build/test/lint/format/secret scan.\n- Appium exploratory evidence and 4.3 hardening checks before release handoff.\n- Appium deferral is not permitted for this run: allow_macos_deferred=false; missing hosted macOS CI simulator evidence blocks release handoff.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_8","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"cd /home/daytona/workspace/.fabro/scratch/01KRK15YVT2214YB2CZ78HWJJM/parallel/implementation_review_fanout/implementation_boilerplate_review && sed -n '1,240p' .workflow/iphone-app-factory/spec.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Product Spec\n\n## Research Evidence\n- Evidence inputs reviewed: App Store reviews, Reddit pain mining, competitor scans, iOS design-pattern synthesis, and the quality bar contract.\n- Evidence confidence: medium-high. Signals are consistent across sources on reliability distrust, anti-autopilot need, ad friction, and relapse after dismissal.\n- Primary target user: heavy sleepers and chronic snoozers facing real-world consequences (work, school, caregiving, shift transitions).\n- Core job-to-be-done: convert `alarm fired` into `awake and executing first morning action`, not just dismissal.\n\n## User Journeys\n- `J-01 Critical Wake`: User creates a strict alarm with mission stack, alarm fires, user completes adaptive mission, passes wake-check, completes first micro-task, and sees reliability timeline entry.\n- `J-02 Relapse Recovery`: User dismisses but ignores wake-check; app escalates (configured louder pattern / repeat challenge), requires re-validation, logs escalation outcome.\n- `J-03 Trust Verification`: User opens reliability ledger and sees per-alarm timeline: scheduled, triggered, mission completion, wake-check status, escalation/failure reason.\n- `J-04 Fast Setup`: New user completes setup wizard with iOS constraint disclosure, permission rationale, and privacy explanation before first alarm activation.\n\n## MVP Scope\n- In scope:\n  - Alarm creation/editing with mission stack and strictness level.\n  - Adaptive mission rotation across at least 3 modalities: cognitive, movement, scan/photo/object.\n  - Post-dismiss wake-check contract with configurable window and escalation.\n  - Reliability ledger with human-readable per-alarm execution logs.\n  - First-task bridge: one user-selected micro-task required after wake verification.\n  - Ad-free critical wake path (active alarm + immediate post-dismiss + wake-check).\n  - Basic weekly wake consistency summary.\n- Non-goals:\n  - Sleep-stage tracking platform.\n  - Public social feed or stranger accountability mechanics.\n  - Wellness content library (stories/sounds/coaching).\n  - Wearable-dependent launch requirements.\n\n## Boilerplate Reuse\n- Base: extend `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro` in `apps/waketask-iphone`; no platform rebuild.\n- Mandatory policy: extend before replace.\n- Rebuilds forbidden without ADR-level justification: auth, payments, AI, storage, networking, localization, settings, design system, DI/composition root.\n- Any proposed net-new infrastructure must include:\n  - Existing module evaluated.\n  - Gap found.\n  - Why extension is not viable.\n  - Replacement cost/benefit and App Store 4.3 impact.\n\n## Design Direction\n- Product tone: calm, serious, high-trust; avoid gimmick and shame framing.\n- UX priorities:\n  - Single clear next action during active alarm.\n  - Large controls, high legibility, high contrast, clear countdown/status.\n  - No monetization interruptions in critical wake path.\n  - Explicit privacy copy for on-device mission validation.\n- Differentiation Contract (4.3 hardening):\n  - `D-01` Reliability ledger is visible and usable in first session.\n  - `D-02` Post-dismiss wake-check escalation is active and configurable.\n  - `D-03` Adaptive anti-autopilot mission rotation changes mission pattern over time.\n  - `D-04` First-task bridge is integrated into wake completion flow.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- `FR-01 Alarm Setup`: User can create, edit, enable, disable alarms with mission stack and strictness.\n  - Verification: UI test creates and edits alarm; persisted state reload confirms values.\n- `FR-02 Mission Engine`: App supports at least 3 mission modalities and rotation logic.\n  - Verification: unit tests validate modality selection and anti-repeat rules.\n- `FR-03 Wake Contract`: Dismissal requires wake-check within configured window; missed check triggers escalation.\n  - Verification: integration test with mocked time path asserts escalation state transition.\n- `FR-04 Reliability Ledger`: Each alarm run writes timeline records with success/failure reason.\n  - Verification: repository integration test asserts schema fields and ordering.\n- `FR-05 First-Task Bridge`: Wake flow is incomplete until selected micro-task marked complete.\n  - Verification: UI test blocks completion until first task done.\n- `FR-06 Ad-Free Critical Path`: No interstitial ads in alarm, dismiss, wake-check flows.\n  - Verification: release audit checklist plus automated string scan for ad-sdk entrypoints in critical flow module.\n- `NFR-01 Performance`: cold launch p95 <= 2.0s on target simulator profile.\n  - Verification: startup metric capture in CI report.\n- `NFR-02 Interaction Latency`: mission interaction response p95 <= 200ms.\n  - Verification: UI performance test with 30 sampled actions.\n- `NFR-03 Stability`: crash-free sessions >= 99.5% in pre-release test runs.\n  - Verification: Appium exploratory + XCTest run logs with crash count = 0 for gate pass.\n- `NFR-04 Accessibility`: Dynamic Type, VoiceOver labels, contrast >= WCAG AA, tap targets >= 44x44 pt for core flows.\n  - Verification: accessibility audit checklist + XCTest assertions where automatable.\n- `NFR-05 Privacy/Data`: mission validation data processed on-device for MVP; no secret values logged.\n  - Verification: code review plus log scan gate with zero violations.\n- `NFR-06 File/Code Quality`: Swift production and test files remain <= 400 lines; Swift 6 strict concurrency preserved.\n  - Verification: lint/build gate and line-count script in CI.\n\n## Appium Exploratory QA\n- Required artifact: `reports/ios/appium-exploratory-report.json`.\n- Pass conditions:\n  - Real simulator/Appium/XCUITest run executed.\n  - `buttons_tapped > 0` and representative coverage of all reachable MVP screens.\n  - `crashes = 0`, `failures = 0`.\n- Required report fields:\n  - `ok`, `buttons_tapped`, `screens_visited`, `crashes`, `failures`, `failures_detail`.\n- Deferral policy:\n  - For this run, deferral is not allowed: allow_macos_deferred=false.\n  - Appium/XCUITest exploratory evidence must come from GitHub Actions hosted macOS iOS simulator evidence.\n  - Local simulator limitations and human testing are not acceptance evidence tonight.\n  - Missing Appium evidence blocks release handoff.\n\n## App Store Readiness\n- 4.3 anti-clone gate must pass:\n  - Differentiation contract (`D-01`..`D-04`) is visible in onboarding, core wake flow, and metadata/screenshots narrative.\n  - Release strings and metadata must not read as generic template alarm clone copy.\n- Compliance and release evidence must include:\n  - `xcodebuild build` pass.\n  - `xcodebuild test` pass.\n  - SwiftLint, SwiftFormat, Qlty, and secret scan all pass as blocking gates.\n  - Privacy disclosures align with actual data behavior.\n- Security handling:\n  - Credential checks are true/false presence only.\n  - No printing/logging/writing of secret values in artifacts.\n\n## Definition of Done\n- Canonical DoD is maintained in `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/definition-of-done.md` and is release-blocking.\n- `Done` requires every checklist item to be verifiably satisfied with evidence artifacts.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
